// Package pages hosts the page-level templ components — each one slots into
// the layout.Layout chrome via Renderer.RenderTempl. Pages take their own
// typed props directly (no opaque `Body any` bag); the home page has no
// per-request data, so Home() takes no arguments.
package pages

// Home is the empty-state landing page rendered when no projects are mounted.
// Populated-state requests are 303-redirected to the first project's overview
// before this ever runs — see web.handleHome.
//
// 1:1 port of templates/pages/home.tmpl: same copy, same class names, same
// hrefs. Layout / styling stay identical until Phase 2 explicitly relaxes
// "behaviour-identical, layout-identical."
templ Home() {
	<section class="empty-state">
		<h1>Welcome to tickets_please</h1>
		<p class="subtitle">No projects are mounted on this server yet. Mount one to get started — humans and LLM agents will share the same audit trail.</p>
		<div class="page-actions">
			<a class="btn btn-primary" href="/p/new">Create a new project</a>
			<a class="btn" href="/p/load">Load an existing project</a>
		</div>
		<p class="footnote">
			Or run <code>tickets_please mcp</code> from a repo containing a
			<code>.tickets_please/project.yaml</code> to bind a session and have
			the project appear in the sidebar.
		</p>
	</section>
}
